Anonymous Mon 04 Apr 2022 03:21:08 No.46671671 Report
Quoted By: >>46671798 >>46671863 >>46671897 >>46671918 >>46679680
Worldbuilding Question:

I don’t want to have Anthros existing along side regular their regular animal counterparts. I don’t think that Dog Anthros would feel comfortable with pet dogs, or Bovine Anthros with cows being used for milk/meat/leather. While I think that an Anthro is to their animal counterpart is what a human is to a chimp, humans (for the most part) don’t use chimps for food and feel chimps (and other great apes) are close enough to humans that they deserve special consideration. I think that Anthros would feel similar about their animal counterparts, bring in all sorts of uncomfortable questions.

So to avoid all that nonsense, in lieu of regular animals I’m considering these options:

Dinosaurs
>+Lots of Dinosaurs, plenty of species to fill any roll, wild animal or domestic
>+Can give the world a land of the lost/fantastic feel
>-Can’t use Dino anthros without running into the original problem
>-No domesticated mammals means no cheese which means no bacon cheese burgers

Prehistoric/Basal/Extinct Forms of existing animals (Aurochs instead of bovine, Eucyon Davis instead of canines, Pseudaelurus for Felines, etc)
>+The animals actually exist, can fit into niches/roles easy
>+An additional degree of separation between anthro and animal while having a sense of verisimilitude
>-Have to research what existed
>-Nobody knows what a Merychippus is without looking it up

Fantasy equivalent of Animals (e.g. it’s not a cow, it’s a herdbest. It has six limbs and goes “brrrrmm” instead of mooing)
>+Can take existing animals and give them a fantasy twist
>+Can mix it up what is used for what, like giant insects for draft animals
>-Most likely to have animals be plot convenient than part of a full ecology
>-If I am making a cow/horse/etc, why not just call it a cow/horse/etc.
